The paper proposes a new data structure for manipulating graphs and describes algorithms for dynamic applications, such as insertions and deletions of vertices or edges, and adjacency queries. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also relies on the arboricity of graphs, which is a measure of how "tree-like" a graph is, suggesting that it could belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The paper also mentions listing cliques, recognizing diamond-free graphs, and finding simple, simplicial, and dominated vertices, which are all related to graph theory and could place the paper in the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-categories. Finally, the paper proposes new static algorithms for counting subgraphs of size 4, recognizing cop-win graphs, and recognizing strongly chordal graphs, which could also place it in the cs.GT (Graph Theory) sub-category.
